Apologies for the necro, but this is an issue that comes up more often than I'd like to see in SCPs, and I think it's worth continuing to bring attention to.

We know the lines well.  (AKA the GOC.) But it's one thing to have the lines, another thing to make them work in practice. I think the main problem I see with some SCPs is that they take these to their conclusion without understanding why they exist.

And I think this is a good example.  arena.

Now, this could be justified if there was reason to believe that the Foundation was gaining key information about the anomaly and making significant progress towards something. Except That's blatant, bald-faced cruelty.

To justify avoiding the termination of an anomaly that wants to be terminated, there has to be something concrete behind it. Testing, information gain, something that justifies the actions and is demonstrably productive (not just testing for the sake of testing). Without that, the takeway becomes  and I don't know what purpose that serves for anyone.







